Docs.summary: Represents the collection of selected items in the .

remarks.format:
## Remarks The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> class stores the selected items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>. The items stored in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> are items contained within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class stores all items displayed in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
The following table is an example of how the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> stores the items of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> as well as their selection states within an example <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
|Index|Item|Selection state within the ListBox| |-----------|----------|----------------------------------------| |0|object1|Unselected| |1|object2|Selected| |2|object3|Unselected| |3|object4|Selected| |4|object5|Selected|
Based on the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> demonstrated in the previous table, the following table demonstrates how the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> would appear.
|Index|Selected item from ObjectCollection| |-----------|-----------------------------------------| |0|object2| |1|object4| |2|object5|
You can use the properties and methods of this class to perform a variety of tasks with the collection. The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection.Contains%2A> method enables you to determine whether an item from the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class is a member of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>. Once you know that the item is located within the collection, you can use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedIndexCollection.IndexOf%2A> method to determine where a specific item within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is stored within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.

You can then use this value when looping through the values of the collection and you need to provide a number of iterations to perform the loop. Unless the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectionMode%2A> property of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is set to `SelectionMode.MultiSimple` or `SelectionMode.MultiExtended`, this property always returns a value of zero (0) or one (1) depending on whether you have a selected item.
